        Procedures and functions allow a program to be broken up into logical units and components of code which can be reused, preventing code duplication. By allowing the program to be broken up into logical units of code which can be named, the process of reasoning about the program can be simplified: given a descriptive name, one can reason about the function as a whole. In addition, the prevention of code reuse means that if there is a bug in the function, instead of having to track down everywhere it is called (where the code would have been duplicated) to fix it, which is error-prone and tedious, one can simply fix it in the function itself.
